summary.seg: This manuscript contains epigrams and brief fragments from the works of the ancient poet Callimachus with annotations on many of his works by Thomas Stanley (1625-1678). Stanley was a poet, historian of philosophy and editor and translator of classical Greek texts. He left such annotations on a number of classical authors, but appears to have paid particular attention to Callimachus. The eminent classicist Richard Bentley (1662-1742) was accused in an anonymous pamphlet of using Stanley's notes without attribution (A Short Account of Dr. Bentley's Humanity and Justice to those Authors who have written before him, with an honest Vindication of Thomas Stanley, Esq., and his Notes on Callimachos (London, 1699)).

support.material: pp. vii-xii, 1-148 Western paper, folded in octavo. Watermark: Crown ( 37 30 ) at the top of the gutter, comparable but not identical to Heawood 1037-1040, 1045-1046. The dated examples among these are dated to 1637.

supportDesc.foliation: The manuscript has been paginated with the numbers i-vi + vii-xii, 1-148 in Arabic and Roman numerals, in black ink (Arabic numerals pp. 1-80) and pencil (Roman numerals, Arabic numerals pp. 81-148). Numerals in ink appear on both recto and verso in the upper outer corner, numerals in pencil on recto only, except for pp. xii and 148.

collation.p: The manuscript consists of 10 quires, of which one is a quinion and the rest are quaternia.

list.item: Quire 68-2 pp. 79-90 The first two folios have been cancelled, without loss of text.
Quire 108-3 pp. 79-90 The last three folios have been cancelled or lost, without loss of text.

supportDesc.condition: There is some creasing, slight water staining and occasional areas of dirt.

layoutDesc.layout:
A single column of 20-26 lines. 125 75
Margins are ruled in red ink.

handNote.p: The manuscript was copied by Thomas Stanley, the Greek text in a western European mixed minuscule.

additions.p: On p. vii is a dedication: my love to you. On p. xi is a general heading: T. Stanlei annotata in Callimachum.
On p. i are some notes by a later hand.

binding.p: 17th-century full leather binding over couched-laminate boards, with marbled pastedowns. There is decorative gold tooling on the boards, the edges and the rebacked spine. The title Notae in Callimachi is tooled in gold on a red label on the spine, and the classmark appears on patches. The edges of the leaves have been gilded.

history.origin: The manuscript was written by the poet and scholar Thomas Stanley (1625-1678) Stanley, Thomas, 1625-1678 at some time between 1639 and 1675.
history.provenance: Stanley's annotations were reportedly used by the classical scholar Richard Bentley (1662-1742) Bentley, Richard, 1662-1742 (A Short Account of Dr. Bentley's Humanity and Justice to those Authors who have written before him, with an honest Vindication of Thomas Stanley, Esq., and his Notes on Callimachos (London 1699)).
